Let’s get vulnerable ->

*Long sappy post ahead*

If you’ve been here for awhile, you know that after my show last year in June I REALLY struggled with getting back on track with eating and overall just struggled mentally. 

I also parted ways with my coach because I had spent so much money in prep that I actually drove myself into debt, and couldn’t afford to stay with him.

From June 11th 2022 to August of 2022 I struggled with binge eating and getting myself to the gym or just feeling any spark of discipline or motivation.

It wasn’t until @darcsport reached out to me in August that I decided enough was enough.

I was done throwing myself a pity party.

I’m not saying that in that moment I decided to be perfectly on top of everything, but I started doing what I loved again which was lifting heavy shit and breaking down my walls.

I didn’t start tracking my food again or eating to fuel my body but it was a step in the right direction.

If you’ve been watching my stories over the past week, you know that Andrew (my boyfriend of 4 years) left for California to start his job while I finish my degree here in Alabama.

Knowing myself I knew this would derail me mentally leading me to hole up in bed and not feed myself as well as I should, so I reached back out to @alexbush__ 

I’ve decided to get back with my coach because instead of wallowing in self pity this next year while I finish my degree, I’m going to take this time to put my head down and work harder than before.

So here is my starting point.

The picture on the left is one week post show at 122.6 pounds after I had been binging for a week and eating until I was in tears from being so painfully full, and the picture on the right is from today at 123.8 with a whole new mentality better than ever.

I’m ready to work harder that ever, and I’m so excited to share this journey with y’all.

#RoadToPro
(But I’m in no rush)

Happy Indigenous Peoples Day!

Danced my little heart out this weekend and managed to snag 3rd place, my first time ever placing!🥹

I almost didn’t go to the pow wow this past weekend, but I’m so glad I did. I had so many great and meaningful conversations with people I’ve never met before, and walked away feeling so loved and seen.

That’s the beautiful thing about native people, they talk to you and treat you like they’ve known you for years, and no matter the distance, you know you’ll see each other again.
